What do you mean by "cache my bundles"?  By default when you install a bundle into the framework it will cache the content of that bundle into the configuration area.  So for example when you do the following ...

BundleContext context = getContext();
Bundle installedBundle = context.installBundle("file:/mybundles/mybundle.jar");

This will copy the content of /mybundles/mybundle.jar to the configuration area of the Equinox framework.  If you would prefer that the content does not get copied into the configuration area then you can use the "reference" protocol that is built into the Equinox framework ...

Bundle referenceBundle = context.installBundle(
                             "reference:file:/mybundles/mybundle.jar");

Or you can create a new reference URL and give your own bundle location string ...

URL referenceURL = new URL("reference:file:/mybundles/mybundle.jar");
Bundle referenceBundle = context.installBundle(
                             "mybundle", referenceURL.openStream());

This will tell the framework that you want to use the content of the bundle from the "referenced" URL without copying the content to the framework cache.  There is a restriction that the referenced URL must be a file URL.  There are also some other issues with this approach.  The framework by default assumes the content of the referenced URL is constant.  It does not support you just overriding a file of a referenced URL and expect it to be detected by the framework.  There is a option to enable timestamp checking that will cause the framework to check timestamps on referenced bundles and if they have changed then it will re-parse bundle manifests, plugin.xml files etc.  This option is osgi.checkConfiguration.  You should set this option in your config.ini to enable the check:

osgi.checkConfiguration=true

Is that what you need?  Or are you requesting something else here?

