I have the majority of changes made locally for IValidator to live on.  If I create a branch (do I have privs?) would that help?

I think at the end of the day the 2 proposals are mostly the same except one is more restrictive.  So we have...

interface IValidator {
    public IStatus validate(Object value, int copyType, int pipelinePosition);
}

or 

interface IBindingListener {
  public IStatus bindEvent(BindingEvent event);
}

I'm not sure I'm following.  I was thinking they were stateless.  So if I had a validation algorithm that needed to run AFTER_GET and BEFORE_CHANGE I could encapsulate this in one validator.  Then I could register it to be notified of all valdiation...

new BindSpec().addTargetValidator(myValidator);

It would then be invoked during every phase and the validator could determine what phases it validates.

We would also still have what we have today...

new BindSpec().addTargetValidator(BindingEvent.PIPELINE_AFTER_GET, myValidator);

to register the validator with just one phase.  This way you're still stating what phase to run the validation for. It just allows the validator to know of the phase as well.  Our default validators won't pay attention to phases.  But I think that domain specific validators (SSN, Phone, etc.) will want to be able to be registered across multiple phases for formatting and duplicate checks.  By expanding the API slightly we can handle both use cases and get rid of the listener API.

I realize there's more to discuss but since I had time I implemented the proposal from comment 30 along with tests.  The APIs look like the following:

public class PipelineEvent {
	public static final int PHASE_PARTIAL_VALIDATE = 1;
	public static final int PHASE_AFTER_GET = 2;
	public static final int PHASE_AFTER_CONVERT = 3;
	public static final int PHASE_BEFORE_CHANGE = 4;
	public static final int PHASE_AFTER_CHANGE = 5;

	public static final int TYPE_COPY_TO_MODEL = 1;
	public static final int TYPE_COPY_TO_TARGET = 2;

	public PipelineEvent(IObservable model, IObservable target, IDiff diff, int eventType) {

	}

	public Object value;
	public final int type;
	public int phase;
	public IStatus status;	
	public final IObservable model;
	public final IObservable target;
	public final IDiff diff;
}

public interface IPipelineFilter {
	public void filter(PipelineEvent event);
}

public class Binding {
        //...

	public abstract void performTargetToModel(int phase);
	public abstract void performModelToTarget(int phase);
}

You can use a filter to validate or convert a value.  Whatever is returned in the PipelineEvent is what is used for the next phase in the pipeline.  Partial validation is a phase in the pipeline rather than a separate event like it was previously.

Also I only have the changes made for ValueBinding so all events aren't yet a part of PipelineEvent (e.g. REMOVE for lists).

Suppose you have the following API:

interface Bird {

  public void fly();

  public void eat();
}

class Seagull implements Bird {

  public void fly() { ... }

  public void eat() { ... }
}

If you plan on implementing several birds, then there isn't much sense in writing a separate test case for each one. Naturally, you just want to test the Bird interface:

abstract class BirdTest {

  protected abstract Bird getBird();

  @Test
  public void testFly() {
    Bird bird = getBird();
    ...
  }

  @Test
  public void testEat() {
    Bird bird = getBird();
    ...
  }
}

class SeagullTest extends BirdTest {

  protected Bird getBird() {
    return new Seagull();
  }
}

This is perfectly acceptable java syntax/structure, and I believe that manually running SeagullTest on JUnit will work fine. However, Eclipse does not recognize Seagull test as a JUnit test, so it cannot be run from within the IDE without a few workarounds. 

If you add a dummy test to Seagull test, the problem is fixed:

class SeagullTest extends BirdTest {

  protected Bird getBird() {
    return new Seagull();
  }

  @Test
  public void dummyTest() {}
}

Eclipse will now let you run the test.

It seems that Eclipse just needs to take into account the entire inheritence tree when determining whether a class can be run as a JUnit test. It should also prevent abstract classes from being run.

The syntax coloring in the JavaScript text editor is confused by escaped (single or double) quotes in regular expressions. Put the following code into the editor and have a look:

    str = str.replace( /&/g, "&amp;" ); 
    str = str.replace( /</g, "&lt;" ); 
    str = str.replace( />/g, "&gt;" ); 
    str = str.replace( /\'/g, "&apos;" ); 
    str = str.replace( /\"/g, "&quot;" ); 
    str = str.replace( /\n/g, "<br>" );

